@NODE SYSREQ "System Requirements"
@{CODE}@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}W - o - r - d - M - a - n - i - a 

@{FG TEXT}Version : @{FG HIGHLIGHT}1.0
@{FG TEXT}Release Date : @{FG HIGHLIGHT}9 September 1996.@{FG TEXT}
@{JLEFT}
@{BG FILL}                                                                            @{BG BACK}

WordMania  is completely system friendly (naturally :) and should run on any
machine  with  Workbench  and  Kickstart  3.0.   It  has  not been tested on
Workbench 2.0, but it might work.

The program needs the following standard system libraries...

@{FG SHINE}Gadtools.library
ASL.Library@{FG TEXT}

@ENDNODE
@NODE HOWTOUSE "How to use the program"
@{CODE}@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}W - o - r - d - M - a - n - i - a 

@{FG TEXT}Version : @{FG HIGHLIGHT}1.0
@{FG TEXT}Release Date : @{FG HIGHLIGHT}9 September 1996.@{FG TEXT}
@{JLEFT}
@{BG FILL}                                                                            @{BG BACK}

@{BODY}WordMania  is  very  simple  to use.  Just run it from Workbench or the CLI.
The program will load and you will be presented with it's main window.  From
here  you  can either enter a string to search for, open the criteria window
for  a  more specific search or open the preference window to adjust the way
the program works.


The Criteria Window runs asynchronously to the main window, meaning that you
can keep it's window open and still use the main window.


The  Preference Window will disable the Main and Criteria windows when it is
opened.


The  program  uses  a dictionary of words as the basis for all it's searchs,
the  format  of  these dictionaries is discussed in the @{" dictionary formats " LINK DICFORMAT}
section  (Spooky,  eh?).   This  dictionary  can either be held in memory or
accessed  from  disk.   When  performing  searchs  the program can utilise a
method  of  fast  section  skipping.  This involves skipping sections of the
dictionary that it doesn't need to look in.  However before this can be used
the  program  needs  to  scan the whole of the dictionary file, this is done
either  by  @{" PreScaning " LINK PFG_PRESCAN}  the  file  or  during  the first full search.  The
information  from  these  scans  is  saved  in the preferences file, so this
scanning only needs to be done when you change/alter the dictionary file.


@ENDNODE
@NODE GADGETS "Program Gadgets"
@{CODE}@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}W - o - r - d - M - a - n - i - a 

@{FG TEXT}Version : @{FG HIGHLIGHT}1.0
@{FG TEXT}Release Date : @{FG HIGHLIGHT}9 September 1996.@{FG TEXT}
@{JLEFT}
@{BG FILL}                                                                            @{BG BACK}

The main window contains the following gadgets and displays...

@{" Search String   " LINK MWG_STRING}	@{" Display         " LINK MWG_DISPLAY}	@{" SEARCH!         " LINK MWG_SEARCH}
@{" Criteria        " LINK MWG_CRITERIA}	@{" Preferences     " LINK MWG_PREFS}	@{" Clear List      " LINK MWG_CLEARLIST}
@{" Search Results  " LINK MWG_RESULTS}	@{" Total Matchs    " LINK MWG_TOTAL}	@{" Exact Matchs    " LINK MWG_EXACT}
@{" Criteria Matchs " LINK MWG_CRITE}	@{" Words Searched  " LINK MWG_WORDS}


The search criteria window contains these gadgets...

@{" Word length greater than " LINK SCG_GREATER}	@{" ...and less than         " LINK SCG_LESS}
@{" MUST have these letters  " LINK SCG_MUST}	@{" In sequence?             " LINK SCG_INSEQ}
@{" Start search in section  " LINK SCG_START}	@{" ...and end in section    " LINK SCG_END}
@{" Only match criteria      " LINK SCG_ONLYMATCH}	@{" Clear All Criteria       " LINK SCG_CLEAR}


The preference window contains these options...

@{" Dictionary File            " LINK PFG_DICTFILE}	@{" Display results as         " LINK PFG_DISPLAYAS}
@{" Load dictionary to memory? " LINK PFG_LOADDICT}	@{" Case sensitive searchs?    " LINK PFG_CASESENSE}
@{" Save preferences on exit?  " LINK PFG_SAVEEXIT}	@{" Include criteria in prefs? " LINK PFG_INCCRIT}
@{" Include length in display? " LINK PFG_INCLEN}	@{" Fast progress display?     " LINK PFG_FASTDIS}
@{" Fast section skip?         " LINK PFG_FASTSKIP}	@{" Pre-scan dictionary file?  " LINK PFG_PRESCAN}
@{" Save                       " LINK PFG_SAVE}	@{" Use                        " LINK PFG_USE}
@{" Cancel                     " LINK PFG_CANCEL}

@ENDNODE
@NODE MENUS "Program Menus"
@{CODE}@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}W - o - r - d - M - a - n - i - a 

@{FG TEXT}Version : @{FG HIGHLIGHT}1.0
@{FG TEXT}Release Date : @{FG HIGHLIGHT}9 September 1996.@{FG TEXT}
@{JLEFT}
@{BG FILL}                                                                            @{BG BACK}

The following menu options are available...

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}'Save All Matchs'@{FG TEXT}
This will save a list containing all the matchs that were found.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}'Save Exact Matchs'@{FG TEXT}
This  will  save  only  those matchs that have an equal length to the search
string.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}'Save Criteria Matchs'@{FG TEXT}
This saves the matchs that fit within the search criteria.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}'About'@{FG TEXT}
Display a requester with information about the program and author.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}'Quit'@{FG TEXT}
Terminates the program.

@ENDNODE
@NODE PATTERNS "Pattern Matching"
@{CODE}@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}W - o - r - d - M - a - n - i - a 

@{FG TEXT}Version : @{FG HIGHLIGHT}1.0
@{FG TEXT}Release Date : @{FG HIGHLIGHT}9 September 1996.@{FG TEXT}
@{JLEFT}
@{BG FILL}                                                                            @{BG BACK}

@{BODY}The  program  uses the standard dos.library pattern matching routines so all
the  patterns  are  the  same  as  the  file  patterns that can be used with
programs like 'copy', 'dir' and in ASL file requesters.


@{CODE}WordMaina can except all of the following patterns in the search string.


	@{FG SHINE}?	@{FG TEXT}Matches a single character.
	@{FG SHINE}#	@{FG TEXT}Matches the following expression 0 or more times.
	@{FG SHINE}(ab|cd)	@{FG TEXT}Matches any one of the items seperated by '|'.
	@{FG SHINE}~	@{FG TEXT}Negates the following expression.  It matches all strings
		that do not match the expression (aka ~(foo) matches all
		strings that are not exactly "foo").
	@{FG SHINE}[abc]	@{FG TEXT}Character class: matches any of the characters in the class.
	@{FG SHINE}[~bc]	@{FG TEXT}Character class: matches any of the characters not in the
		class.
	@{FG SHINE}a-z	@{FG TEXT}Character range (only within character classes). 
	@{FG SHINE}%	@{FG TEXT}Matches 0 characters always (useful in "(foo|bar|%)").
	@{FG SHINE}*	@{FG TEXT}Synonym for "#?", not available by default in 2.0.  Available
		as an option that can be turned on.

@{BODY}"Expression" in the above table means either a single character (ex:  "#?"),
or   an   alternation  (ex:   "#(ab|cd|ef)"),  or  a  character  class  (ex:
"#[a-zA-Z]").

@ENDNODE
@NODE EXAMPLES "Examples"
@{CODE}@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}W - o - r - d - M - a - n - i - a 

@{FG TEXT}Version : @{FG HIGHLIGHT}1.0
@{FG TEXT}Release Date : @{FG HIGHLIGHT}9 September 1996.@{FG TEXT}
@{JLEFT}
@{BG FILL}                                                                            @{BG BACK}

Some examples of pattern matching....

@{CODE}@{FG SHINE}@{U}Example 1@{UU}@{FG TEXT}

	@{B}@{FG HIGHLIGHT}#?it@{UB}@{FG TEXT}

@{BODY}This  will  search  for  all  words ending in 'it'.  '*it' would also do the
same.  WordMania would output the following...  (and many more!)


@{CODE}@{FG FILL}Accredit
Acquit
Admit
Adroit
Affidavit


@{FG SHINE}@{U}Example 2@{UU}@{FG TEXT}

	@{B}@{FG HIGHLIGHT}???it@{UB}@{FG TEXT}

@{BODY}This  will  search for all five letter words ending in 'it'.  Another method
of  doing this would be to use '*it' and set the word length to greater than
4 and less than 6.


WordMania would output the following...  (and many more!)


@{CODE}@{FG FILL}Admit
Audit
Await
Befit
Bruit


@{FG SHINE}@{U}Example 3 - Solving The Suns' SUNDIAL puzzles@{UU}@{FG TEXT}

	tbaihweit

@{BODY}Set   the  @{"  Word  length  greater  than  " LINK SCG_GREATER}  gadget  to  3  and  set  the
@{" MUST have these letters " LINK SCG_MUST} to 't'.  Now press @{"SEARCH!" LINK MWG_SEARCH}.  This will initiate a
search  that  will  find  all  the  anagrams  of 'tbaihweit' that consist of
atleast 4 letters and contain the letter 't'.


WordMania would output the following...  (and many more!)


@{CODE}@{FG FILL}Abet
Bait
Bate
Bath
Whet
Whit
White
Whitebait
With

@ENDNODE
@NODE DICFORMAT "Dictionary Formats"
@{CODE}@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}W - o - r - d - M - a - n - i - a 

@{FG TEXT}Version : @{FG HIGHLIGHT}1.0
@{FG TEXT}Release Date : @{FG HIGHLIGHT}9 September 1996.@{FG TEXT}
@{JLEFT}
@{BG FILL}                                                                            @{BG BACK}

@{BODY}The dictionaries are straight forward ASCII text files that contain a single
word on each line.


The  file  must  be  sorted alphabetically.  The words may consist of upper,
lower or mixed characters, although this will affect case-sensitive searchs.


Any  lines  that  start  with  a  non-alphabetical character (such as ;.,?/~
!"Ł$%^&*(), etc.) are ignore by WordMania.


This   dictonary   format  is  fairly  standard  amongst  most  PD/Shareware
WordProcessors  and  spell  checkers  (with  the  possible  exception of the
non-alphabetical lines).


The  lists that WordMania saves out also take this format with the first few
lines used as header information (all prefixed with ';').  These saved files
can  be  fed  back into WordMania as dictionary files.  Thus allowing you to
perform  searchs  on  subsets  of  the  dictionary that have been previously
created and saved.

@ENDNODE
@NODE HISTORY "Program History"
@{CODE}@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}W - o - r - d - M - a - n - i - a 

@{FG TEXT}Version : @{FG HIGHLIGHT}1.0
@{FG TEXT}Release Date : @{FG HIGHLIGHT}9 September 1996.@{FG TEXT}
@{JLEFT}
@{BG FILL}                                                                            @{BG BACK}

