@NODE MWG_STRING "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}Search String@{FG TEXT}@{UB}


This  is  the  string  that you want to perform an anagram search or pattern
match on.

@ENDNODE
@NODE MWG_DISPLAY "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}Display@{FG TEXT}@{UB}


WordMania  can  display  either  'Criteria  Matchs', 'All Matchs', or 'Exact
Matchs'. These are explained below.


@{CODE}@{FG HIGHLIGHT}'Criteria Matchs'@{FG TEXT}
@{BODY}This  is  all  the  words that match the search criteria as specified in the
Criteria Window.


@{CODE}@{FG HIGHLIGHT}'All Matchs'@{FG TEXT}
@{BODY}These are all matchs found that match the search string (be they anagrams or
pattern  matches).   This  list  will  include words that both match and not
match the criteria.


@{CODE}@{FG HIGHLIGHT}'Exact Matchs'@{FG TEXT}
@{BODY}These  are  words that match the search string and are the exact same length
as the search string.


Also see the save options in the @{" menus " LINK MENUS}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE MWG_SEARCH "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}SEARCH!@{FG TEXT}@{UB}


This  button  will  start  the  search  engine.  A 'Progress Window' will be
displayed  and will update the progress of the search, during the search the
'Display  List'  and  'Totals'  will  be update also.  The 'Progress Window'
contains an 'Abort Button' and pressing this will abort the search.


@ENDNODE
@NODE MWG_CRITERIA "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}Criteria@{FG TEXT}@{UB}


This button opens/closes the 'Search Criteria Window'.  This window also you
to  further  specifiy  the  search  parameters  for  the search engine.  The
'Search  Criteria  Window' runs asynchronous with the 'Main Program Window',
thus it can remain open through out the programs operation.


@{CODE}The 'Search Criteria Window' contains the following gadgets.

@{" Word length greater than " LINK SCG_GREATER}
@{" ...and less than         " LINK SCG_LESS}
@{" MUST have these letters  " LINK SCG_MUST}
@{" In sequence?             " LINK SCG_INSEQ}
@{" Start search in section  " LINK SCG_START}
@{" ...and end in section    " LINK SCG_END}
@{" Only match criteria      " LINK SCG_ONLYMATCH}
@{" Clear All Criteria       " LINK SCG_CLEAR}

@ENDNODE
@NODE MWG_PREFS "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}Preferences@{FG TEXT}@{UB}


This  opens  the  preferences window, from here you can control the way that
'WordMania' works.


@{CODE}The 'Preferences Window' contains the following gadgets.

@{" Dictionary File            " LINK PFG_DICTFILE}
@{" Display results as         " LINK PFG_DISPLAYAS}
@{" Load dictionary to memory? " LINK PFG_LOADDICT}
@{" Case sensitive searchs?    " LINK PFG_CASESENSE}
@{" Save preferences on exit?  " LINK PFG_SAVEEXIT}
@{" Include criteria in prefs? " LINK PFG_INCCRIT}
@{" Include length in display? " LINK PFG_INCLEN}
@{" Fast progress display?     " LINK PFG_FASTDIS}
@{" Fast section skip?         " LINK PFG_FASTSKIP}
@{" Pre-scan dictionary file?  " LINK PFG_PRESCAN}
@{" Save                       " LINK PFG_SAVE}
@{" Use                        " LINK PFG_USE}
@{" Cancel                     " LINK PFG_CANCEL}

@ENDNODE
@NODE MWG_CLEARLIST "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}Clear List@{FG TEXT}@{UB}


@{BODY}This button will clear the current 'Search Results' window and memory.
@ENDNODE
@NODE MWG_RESULTS "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}Search Results@{FG TEXT}@{UB}


This  is  the  list  of  results  from  the last search.  The display can be
switched thru three different display types using the 'Display' button.  The
current results can be cleared using the @{" Clear List " LINK MWG_CLEARLIST} button.
@ENDNODE
@NODE MWG_TOTAL "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}Total Matchs@{FG TEXT}@{UB}


This is the total of all the words found that match the search string.
@ENDNODE
@NODE MWG_EXACT "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}Exact Matchs@{FG TEXT}@{UB}


This  is the total of all the words found that match the exact length of the
search string.
@ENDNODE
@NODE MWG_CRITE "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}Criteria Matchs@{FG TEXT}@{UB}


This is the total of all the words found that match the search criteria.
@ENDNODE
@NODE MWG_WORDS "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}Words Searched@{FG TEXT}@{UB}


This is the total number of words that have been searched.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SCG_GREATER "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}Greater than @{FG TEXT}@{UB}


This  specifies  that the length of each word found must be greater than the
number  in the gadget.  So if you only wanted words that are 4 characters or
more, then you'd specify a value of 3 in this gadget.  A value of zero means
that there is no minimum length.


Defaults to 0.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SCG_LESS "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}Less than@{FG TEXT}@{UB}


This  specifies  that  the  length  of each word found must be less than the
number  in  the  gadget.   So if you only wanted words that are 6 letters or
less, then you'd specify a value of 7 in this gadget.  A value of zero means
that there is no maximum length.


Defaults to 0.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SCG_MUST "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}MUST have these letters@{FG TEXT}@{UB}


This string gadgets should contain letters that must occur in the words that
are  found.   Every  word that matchs the search string will then be checked
with  this  string  to  ensure  that  it  has these letters in it also.  For
example  if  you  only wanted words that contained all the vowels then you'd
put  "aeiou"  in  this  gadget,  and the criteria results would only contain
words with all the vowels in.


Defaults to an empty string.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SCG_INSEQ "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}In sequence?@{FG TEXT}@{UB}


This  is  used in conjunction with the @{" MUST have these letters " LINK SCG_MUST} gadget.  If
this  is  ticked  then  the contents of the 'MUST have these letters' gadget
must  occur  in  order and together as a word.  For example if you only want
words  that contained 'word' within them then you'd set the 'MUST have these
letters' gadget with the string "word" and set this gadget.  Then only words
that  had  the  string  "word" within them would be chosen.  Whereas if this
gadget wasn't checked then any word that had a 'w','o','r' and 'd' within it
(in any order) would be valid.


Defaults to off.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SCG_START "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}Search section start@{FG TEXT}@{UB}


This  allows  you to specify a particular section of the dictionary to start
the  search  in.   The  section is specified with a letter (eg.  'h').  This
gadget is only available after the full dictionary has been scanned.


Defaults to 'A'.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SCG_END "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}Search section end@{FG TEXT}@{UB}


This  allows you to specify a particular section of the dictionary where the
search  will  end.  The section is specified with a letter (eg.  'h').  This
gadget is only available after the full dictionary has been scanned.


Defaults to 'Z'.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SCG_ONLYMATCH "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}Only match the criteria@{FG TEXT}@{UB}


Normally,  when  this gadget is unchecked, the search engine keeps a list of
all  matching words whether they match the criteria or not.


This  means  that  if you were looking for all the words that ended in 'ary'
and  where  atleast  10  characters long, you would set the search string to
"*ary" and set the @{" Word length greater than " LINK SCG_GREATER} to 9.  The search engine would
then produce a list of all the words that matched '*ary' and a seperate list
of  the  ones  that  matched and where greater than 9.


However  if  you  where  just  looking  for  all words than where atleast 10
characters  long,  you'd use a search string of '*' and set the greater than
gadget  to  9.Now  this would match ALL words in the dictionary and would be
rather slow and consume a vast amount of memory.


So  in this case you would only want the search engine to match the criteria
and  not the search string and the criteria, and you'd do this by using this
gadget.


Defaults to off.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SCG_CLEAR "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}Clear all the criteria@{FG TEXT}@{UB}


This  resets  all  the  gadgets  in  the  criteria  window  to there default
settings.
@ENDNODE
@NODE PFG_DICTFILE "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}Dictionary file to use for search@{FG TEXT}@{UB}


This  is the dictionary file that the program uses to find it's words.  This
file  is  essential  for  the  program to function.  The program can use any
dictionary file that is suitably formatted.  See @{" Dictionary formats " LINK DICFORMAT}.


Defaults to "Dictionary".
@ENDNODE
@NODE PFG_DISPLAYAS "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}Display results as @{FG TEXT}@{UB}


@{BODY}This specifies the display style for the results window.

@{CODE}The words can be displayed in the following formats:

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}'Capitalised'@{FG TEXT}
This will capitalise each word (i.e.  Moonchild)

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}'UpperCase'@{FG TEXT}
This will change the word so that it is all uppercase (i.e.  MOONCHILD)

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}'LowerCase'@{FG TEXT}
This will change the word so that it is all lowercase (i.e.  moonchild)

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}'Unaltered'@{FG TEXT}
@{BODY}This  will leave the word unformatted so that it is displayed in exactly the
same way as it appears in the dictionary file.


This  display format is also the format used in the output file of any lists
that are saved.


Defaults to "Capitalised".
@ENDNODE
@NODE PFG_LOADDICT "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}Load dictionary into memory?@{FG TEXT}@{UB}


If  this  gadget is checked then the program will attempt to load the entire
dictionary  file  into  memory  and use it there, if the dictionary file has
been  compacted  with Stonecracker then it will be decrunched to memory.  If
this  gadget is unchecked then the dictionary will be access from disk as it
is needed.


Please  note:   If the dictionary file is Stonecracker then this option must
be set, as the file cannot be accessed from disk in this compacted format.


Defaults to on.
@ENDNODE
@NODE PFG_CASESENSE "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}Case sensitive searchs?@{FG TEXT}@{UB}


This  specifies  whether  the  program  should  treat  all  strings  as case
sensitive  or not.  I don't think there is much point in this option, but it
might be of use to someone, I put it in for completeness, actually I haven't
really tested it properly! (Sorry :).


Defaults to off.
@ENDNODE
@NODE PFG_SAVEEXIT "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}Save prefs on exit@{FG TEXT}@{UB}


If  this  option  is  set  then  the  program  will  automatically  save the
preferences (and criteria if applicable) when you quit the program.


Defaults to off.
@ENDNODE
@NODE PFG_INCCRIT "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}Include the criteria in the prefs@{FG TEXT}@{UB}


This option will save the criteria with the preferences.  Therefore when you
next  run  the  program the criteria will be set to the values that you used
when you saved the preferences.


Defaults to on.
@ENDNODE
@NODE PFG_INCLEN "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}Include the length in the search results display@{FG TEXT}@{UB}


Chosing this option will add the length in characters to the words displayed
in the results window.


Defaults to on.
@ENDNODE
@NODE PFG_FASTDIS "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}Fast progress display@{FG TEXT}@{UB}


When  this  option is active (i.e.  ticked) the program will only update the
display  when  it  matchs  a  word.   If  this option is not chosen then the
program  will  update  the  'Words  Searched'  total after each word that it
checks.   It's  best  to  use  the @{" Fast progress display " LINK PFG_FASTDIS} on most machines,
unless you've got a really fast machine in which case feel free to show off!


Defaults to on.
@ENDNODE
@NODE PFG_FASTSKIP "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}Fast section skip@{FG TEXT}@{UB}


When  this option is on the search engine will automatically skip dictionary
sections  that is doesn't need to look at.  For example if the search string
doesn't  contain  the  letter  'a'  then  there's  no point looking at words
starting with the letter 'a', so this section will skipped (Clever, eh?  :).
This  fast skipping will only work if the dictionary has been fully scanned,
this  is either done with the prescan option or after the first full search.
Dictionary section offset are saved with the preference file.


Defaults to on.
@ENDNODE
@NODE PFG_PRESCAN "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}Pre-scan dictionary file@{FG TEXT}@{UB}


In  order  for WordMania to perform at is best it needs to know the position
of  each dictionary section within the dictionary.  When the dictionary file
is  changed  or the load to memory flag is changed, WordMania can optionally
scan  the  dictionary  file  after  you close the Preference window, this is
quicker  than  a  normal search and allows WordMania to perform fast section
skips  and  allows  you to choose a start and end section.  If you turn this
option  off  then  WordMania  will update it's internal list during the next
FULL dictionary search.


Defaults to on.
@ENDNODE
@NODE PFG_SAVE "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}Save preferences@{FG TEXT}@{UB}


This   will   save   the   changes   that  you  have  made  into  the  files
'ENVARC:WordMania.Prefs'  and  'ENV:WordMania.Prefs'  and  return you to the
main window.

@ENDNODE
@NODE PFG_USE "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}Use preferences@{FG TEXT}@{UB}


This   will   use  the  changes  that  you  have  made  by  saving  them  to
'ENV:WordMania.Prefs' and return you to the main window.

@ENDNODE
@NODE PFG_CANCEL "Program Gadgets"
@{FG SHINE}@{B}Cancel preference changes.@{FG TEXT}@{UB}


This  will  cancel  the  changes  that  you have made and return to the main
window.

@ENDNODE

